    "abstract": [],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "empiric anticoagulation using heparin in patients with COVID-19 and elevated d-dimers suggest lower mortality [5] , though pulmonary artery embolism was not investigated. Does COVID-19 mimic a peripheral or segmental pulmonary embolism or are subpleural triangular consolidations actually signs for pulmonary embolism?",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 110,
                    "end": 113,
                    "text": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "In order to address this issue of immediate therapeutic relevance, we performed a bedside snapshot study and screened all SARS-CoV-2-positive patients on mechanical ventilation with elevated d-dimer levels for the presence of multiple subpleural consolidations. Three out of 10 patients met the inclusion criteria. Baseline characteristics were age 59-60 years, d-dimers > 35.2 mg/l, pulmonary artery pressure estimated by transthoracic echocardiography 35-54 mmHg, no d-signs. None of the patients suffered from coagulopathy or clinical signs for thrombosis, and all were on prophylactic heparin therapy. Since likelihood for pulmonary embolism of these patients was considered medium to high, all patients underwent a chest contrasted computed tomography, which detected segmental pulmonary artery embolisms in all three patients.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        },
        {
            "text": "Of course, we cannot rule out coincidental occurrence of pulmonary embolism. However, pulmonary artery embolism might be a specific complication of COVID-19. We believe that the incidence of pulmonary embolism in COVID-19 patients has to be further investigated. In patients with elevated d-dimers and subpleural consolidations in lung ultrasonography, further diagnostic workup of a potential pulmonary embolism might be advised. Therefore, lung ultrasonography proposed by Peng et al. might be an addition rather than a replacement for computed tomography.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": ""
        }
    ],
